{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem requires finding a sequence of sibling merges to transform one tree into another. This involves identifying which nodes in the initial tree must be merged to match the structure and values of the final tree. I will split this into a logic helper for the tree transformation strategy and an implementation helper for the tree data structures and output formatting.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "logic_helper",
      "instructions": "Develop the core algorithm to determine the sequence of merge operations. Given the initial tree and the final tree, identify which sibling nodes in the initial tree must be merged to result in the nodes present in the final tree. The algorithm must account for the rule that a merge keeps the larger value and unions the children. Since a valid sequence is guaranteed, focus on a bottom-up or top-down approach to identify which nodes in the initial tree are 'lost' through merging to form the target nodes. Return a list of pairs of node values representing the required merges."
    },
    {
      "label": "implementation_helper",
      "instructions": "Write the Python boilerplate to handle input and output for the tree merging problem. Implement a robust tree representation using adjacency lists or parent pointers. The code must read the number of test cases, the initial tree edges, and the final tree edges. It should then call the logic function and print the number of operations followed by each pair of merged nodes on a new line. Ensure the solution handles multiple test cases and adheres to the constraints (N up to 1000)."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Integrate the logic_helper's algorithm into the implementation_helper's structure. The final main.py should use the tree representation to parse the input, pass the tree structures to the logic algorithm to obtain the list of merge operations, and then print the results in the exact format required by the problem statement."
}

